This has been an Android issue since MG3.5 (all was good in 3.4). Sound effects usually play fine the first time they play and then hardly ever work after that. Clicking a button that repeatedly plays a sound effect will eventually crash the device too, with the following error:

 AL.Source (SourceId, ALSource3f.Position, _pan, 0, 0.1f);
        ALHelper.CheckError("Failed to set source pan.");

Manually setting the pan for each sound effect stops this crash but the sound effect still only plays occasionally.

Calling Exit() too soon seems to prevent the game from completely closing, as the process still lives on.

Tested on MonoGame 3.5 and 3.6.

```
using Microsoft.Xna.Framework;

// This example simply adds a red rectangle to the screen
// then updates it's position along the X axis each frame.
namespace Game1
{
	public class Game1 : Game
	{
		GraphicsDeviceManager graphics;

		public Game1()
		{
			graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager(this);
			Content.RootDirectory = "Content";
		}

		protected override void Update(GameTime gameTime)
		{
			Exit();
		}
	}
}
```

If you run this w/o debugging ( does not happen w/ debugging oddly ), the window quickly appears and closes, but the process will still exist in the Task Manager indefinitely until you end the task.

When I call graphics.ApplyChanges() while in fullscreen, despite having graphics.IsFullScreen = true, the game reverts back to windowed. This usually happens right when I call .ApplyChanges() again, but may occasionally take more attempts. 

While in this state, the game is effectively windowed, but the .IsFullScreen property is still true. The problem persists until I set .IsFullScreen back to false, apply, set it back to true and apply again. It's especially bothersome when a user tries to change the resolution while in fullscreen, as this action requires an .ApplyChanges() call while already in fullscreen, thus triggering the problem. The only workaround I see for this is to hop to windowed and back, but this looks very ugly.

To replicate, create a new project and add the following to the Game1 class (rewriting the existing functions where necessary):
     
    KeyboardState last_state;

    protected override void Initialize() {
        last_state = Keyboard.GetState();
        base.Initialize();
    }

    protected override void Update(GameTime gameTime) {

        if(Keyboard.GetState().IsKeyDown(Keys.Enter) && !last_state.IsKeyDown(Keys.Enter)) {
            graphics.IsFullScreen = true;
            graphics.ApplyChanges();
        }
        last_state = Keyboard.GetState();

        base.Update(gameTime);
    }

When running the game, pressing Enter the first time will trigger fullscreen as intended. Pressing Enter again (or in some cases, several times) will trigger the problem. The screen is back to windowed and stays there no matter how many times you press Enter.

It would be nice if we can get color by its name (string).

A good example would be scripting. You get the color from a file as a string and you have to convert it to Color. Right now the only way to achieve this is to use Reflection which is both slow and error-prone (you risk getting a non-color property for instance, so you have to check) or make a library class (basically a dictionary) and enter all of them on your own. The second solution is fine if you want to support only a handful of colors, but it will become a real chore to input if you want to have all 140 of them.

I have a few ideas of how to implement this:
1. Use static Dictionary<string, Color> to store the colors. The static constructor will set the colors in the dictionary and the color properties will become just getters that will get the color from the dictionary. This way getting the color will be somewhat slower than it is now since it a lookup in the dictionary have to be made.

Example:
```c#
    /// <summary>
    /// Colors library
    /// </summary>
    private static Dictionary<string, Color> Colors = new Dictionary<string, Color>();
    
    . . . .

    /// <summary>
    /// Transparent color (R:0,G:0,B:0,A:0).
    /// </summary>
    public static Color Transparent
    {
        get { return Colors["transparent"]; }
    }

    . . . .

    /// <summary>
    /// Get color by name.
    /// </summary>
    public static Color Parse(string name)
    {
        name = name.ToLower();
        if (Colors.Contains(name))
        {
            return Colors[name];
        }
        else
        {
            new ArgumentException("Color not found.");
        }
    }
```

2. The same as option 1 but the color properties have setters which populate the dictionary beside setting the property's field. This way it still have the original performance when getting color by its property, but the code is uglier: a lot of copy/paste and the setter have hidden behavior (adding a value to a dictionary). But I think it is still the better solution since the setter is private.

Example:
```c#
    /// <summary>
    /// Colors library
    /// </summary>
    private static Dictionary<string, Color> Colors = new Dictionary<string, Color>();
    
    . . . .

    private static Color transparent;

    /// <summary>
    /// Transparent color (R:0,G:0,B:0,A:0).
    /// </summary>
    public static Color Transparent
    {
        get { return transparent; }
        private set
        {
            transparent = value;
            Colors["transparent"] = value;
        }
    }

    . . . .

    /// <summary>
    /// Get color by name.
    /// </summary>
    public static Color Parse(string name)
    {
        name = name.ToLower();
        if (Colors.Contains(name))
        {
            return Colors[name];
        }
        else
        {
            new ArgumentException("Color not found.");
        }
    }
```

3. Use reflection to find the color. This way the only change made would be to write the methods, but there would be a big performance penalty because of the reflection. Personally, I don't like this solution at all, although probably it's the easiest to implement.

If the admins give it a go, I can implement one of the options (preferably the second) and make a pull request.

1. Create a new android monogame project.
2. In Activity1.cs add this
        public override void OnBackPressed()
        {            
            // break point;
        }
Launch the app and hit the hardware back button. 

[Expected] break point is hit and nothing happens (since base is not called)
[Actual] break point never hit, leaving the app

This blocks adding a custom exist confirmation 

The workaround is to use the GamePad.GetState(PlayerIndex.One).Buttons.Back == ButtonState.Pressed in the update call instead.
